Welcome to the Personal Project - OptiMarket: Uncovering the Ultimate Marketing Approach¶

Hello! I'm Ayumu Justin Ueda, a Data Science student at UC Berkeley. You can find my profile on (https://www.linkedin.com/in/ayumu-ueda-ab1879224/).

In this project, as a data scientist at a car insurance company, I've been provided with last year's data documenting the outcomes of marketing campaigns involving various types of strategies (a combination of insurance renewal plans - Offer1 and Offer2, and different sales channels - Agent, Branch, Call Center, Email).

Objective:¶

My objective is to enhance the KPI, specifically the acceptance rate of offers, in the upcoming marketing phase by identifying the most effective combinations of customer segments and marketing strategies (a combination of offer type and sales channel).

Project Overview:¶

1. Customer segmentation for pinpointing optimal marketing strategies in each category:¶

Skills Applied:

  • Parametric Statistical Inference(Test of Homogeneity, Chi Square Test)
  • K-means Clustering
  • Principal Component Analysis (PCA)

Skills Applied:

  • Parametric Statistical Inference(Anova one sided test)

Conclusion for this section:

After conducting A/B testing on the marketing campaign, it's evident that Promotion 1 is the most effective in increasing sales.

I have decided to implement Promotion 1 for the email marketing campaign.

Test of homogenity (chi-square test)¶

If distribution of acceptance rate by various type of marketing strategies changes depending on another factor like education, another factor like educational background influences on their preference of the our marketing strategies. For instance, people with a bachelors degree tend to prefer the offer2 through E-mail.

Let's test if customer's education affect the distribution of acceptance rate by marketing strategies by test of homogenity (chi-square test) (https://shorturl.at/mXYZ8)¶

Null and Alternative hypothesis for this test

  • Null hypothesis: there is not significant difference in the distribution of acceptance rate by marketing strategy among customers with five different educational background

  • Alternative hypothesis : there is significant difference in the distribution of acceptance rate by marketing strategy among customers with five different educational background

Conduct chi-square test¶

In [101]:
significant_col = []
for col in df.columns:
  if col == "Response" or col == "Marketing Strategy":
    continue
  else:
    observed_data = df.groupby(["Marketing Strategy", col]).sum()["Response"].unstack(col)
    observed_data
    chi2_stat, p_value, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(observed_data)
    if p_value < 0.05:
      significant_col.append(col)
      print(f"{col} is significant")
    else:
      print(f"{col} is not significant")

Given the similar data composition for each promotion, conducting A/B testing becomes crucial for deriving meaningful insights and identifying the most effective promotion method

conduct ANOVA test (parametric)¶

Before proceeding with A/B testing, I aim to confirm that each promotion yields distinct outcomes. To achieve this, I've opted for a one-sided ANOVA test.

Ensuring that the data adheres to a normal distribution is crucial to meet the essential assumption for ANOVA (Analysis of Variance).¶

Conduct Kruskal-Wallis test (non-parametric)¶

However, it's challenging to determine if provided histogram is normally distributed by our eye. Thus, I have opted for a non-parametric test, specifically the Kruskal-Wallis test.

In [124]:
stats.kruskal(promotion1['SalesInThousands'], promotion2['SalesInThousands'], promotion3['SalesInThousands'])
Out[124]:
KruskalResult(statistic=53.29475169322799, pvalue=2.6741866266697816e-12)

Conduct A/B testing¶

The above test indicates a significant difference among these methods. To determine the preferable method, I will conduct an A/B test and analyze the results

Bootstrapping¶

In [129]:
def one_simulated_difference_of_means(shuffled_labels):
    shuffled_table = pd.DataFrame({"Promotion":shuffled_labels.tolist(), "SalesInThousands":promotion_a_b_test['SalesInThousands']})
    shuffled_table = shuffled_table.groupby("Promotion").mean()
    return (shuffled_table.loc[1] - shuffled_table.loc[3]).item()
In [130]:
sales_differences = np.array([])

repetitions = 1000
for i in np.arange(repetitions):
    shuffled_labels = promotion_a_b_test.sample(frac=1, replace=True, random_state=i)['Promotion']
    new_difference = one_simulated_difference_of_means(shuffled_labels)
    sales_differences = np.append(sales_differences, new_difference)
In [131]:
plt.figure(figsize=(4,4))
plt.hist(sales_differences,bins=50)
plt.scatter(test_statistic, 0, color='red', s=40, zorder=3)

In [132]:
p_value = 1 - np.count_nonzero(sales_differences <= test_statistic) / repetitions
print(f"p-value is {p_value}")

p-value is 0.06000000000000005

With a significance level of 10%, the obtained p-value is small enough to reject the null hypothesis. Thus, I infer that Promotion 1 is more effective than Promotion 3 in generating higher sales.

A/B Testing Results:¶

After conducting A/B testing on the marketing campaign, it's evident that Promotion 1 is the most effective in increasing sales.

Chosen Marketing Strategy:¶

I have decided to implement Promotion 1 for the email marketing campaign.
